        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  To define the abstract OCREngine contract and provide a factory function for creating OCR engine instances by name — enabling decoupled multi-engine OCR without hardcoding Tesseract. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  OCR engine abstraction: interface definition (recognize_page, recognize_cells), factory for instantiation. \par \b Input\/ \:  Engine name (str) and configuration dict. \par \b Output\/ \:  OCREngine subclass instance. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_TYPE(9): OCRResult, OCRLine, OCRWord; INSTANTIATES(8): TesseractEngine] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>get_ocr_engine(&quot;tesseract&quot;, config) ALWAYS returns a TesseractEngine instance.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>get_ocr_engine(unknown_name, config) ALWAYS raises ValueError.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>OCREngine subclasses MUST implement both recognize_page() and recognize_cells(). \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why abstract base class + factory instead of a simple callable? A: Strategy Pattern allows swapping OCR backends without touching orchestration code. Factory centralizes engine registration — new engines just add themselves to the registry. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v2.6.2 – Initial creation: OCREngine ABC + get_ocr_engine() factory] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 10[Abstract base class for OCR engines] =&gt; OCREngine FUNC 10[Factory returns OCREngine instance by name] =&gt; get_ocr_engine \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[get_ocr_engine]: PdfImageReader (Init) → CreateEngine(&quot;tesseract&quot;) → TesseractEngine ready</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>[OCREngine]: Developer → ImplementNewEngine → RegisterInFactory → New engine available </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
